  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3533292519" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3533292519" />
    <a title="Neil" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9822153-neil"><img alt="Neil" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442951400p2/9822153.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3533292519?book_show_action=true">Sep 13, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Neil" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Neil" href="/user/show/9822153-neil">Neil</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3533292519" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2821225889545453217">This is a very odd but ultimately outstanding book about an African-American elevator inspector. <br/><br/>The opening 100 pages kept me asking lots of questions and wondering what I was reading, but as Whitehead&apos;s narrative continued, I eventually became hooked on the protagonist and her bizarre journey to unravel a mystery surrounding an elevator accident at a brand new building, a building that she herself had recently inspected. The final 50 pages were gripping, and the revelations that they dispense </span>
  <span id="freeText2821225889545453217" style="display:none">This is a very odd but ultimately outstanding book about an African-American elevator inspector. <br /><br />The opening 100 pages kept me asking lots of questions and wondering what I was reading, but as Whitehead's narrative continued, I eventually became hooked on the protagonist and her bizarre journey to unravel a mystery surrounding an elevator accident at a brand new building, a building that she herself had recently inspected. The final 50 pages were gripping, and the revelations that they dispense to the reader convinced me that this was a classic. I especially liked the last few pages. <br /><br />Lila Mae is a sympathetic protagonist who has played by all the rules and lived a life so focused and disciplined because her white colleagues are rooting for her to fail, and the restrained and often cryptic narrative follows her into a labyrinth of betrayals, moneyed interests, violence, and American history.<br /><br />There's a hard-boiled element of the novel, but the events are also punctuated by hallucinatory recollections, one of them involving a racist "follies" night for elevator inspectors and another a strange encounter in a dance hall seemingly designed to lessen the woes of aging men. My sense is that this aspect of the novel is what gets it compared to Ellison's _Invisible Man_. The emphasis on elevator inspection as a powerful, high calling also seems to position this in some sort of different reality--one website calls _The Intuitionist_ speculative fiction--but I might be inclined to call it weird fiction given the resemblances to Mieville's _The City and the City_. <br /><br />I was sent this book as part of the Powell's Indiespensible Book box that was organized around Whitehead's _The Nickel Boys_, and I'm very glad they included it. It's outstanding and should be required reading for anyone who wants to encounter a good, weird mystery that ultimately explores intriguing questions about race in the US. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2821225889545453217" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


